// Quick-start profile selection. Sets sensible defaults for many
// settings throughout the rest of the installer. The user can still
// fine-tune every option later in the «Configuration Categories» menu;
// the profile only changes which checkboxes start out checked, it does
// not hide any choice.
//
// Exactly one of these five settings will be #true at any time
// (radiolist semantics). All other Ditana settings reference these
// flags from their `default-value` expressions.

- name="profile-default" \
  dialog-name="User Profile" \
  short-description="Standard - Typical Linux user" \
  long-description="""
The recommended profile for most users.

Wayfire is preselected as the desktop environment, all standard Ditana features are enabled
(encryption prompt, ZFS file system on LTS kernels, Ditana Assistant where supported,
LibreWolf, LibreOffice, foot under Wayland and Alacritty under XFCE).

Equivalent to leaving the original Ditana defaults untouched.
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="" \
  default-value=#true {
    arch-packages ""
}

- name="profile-windows" \
  dialog-name="User Profile" \
  short-description="Coming from Windows - Familiar desktop layout" \
  long-description="""
Geared towards users migrating from Microsoft Windows.

Defaults that change vs. Standard:
 - XFCE preselected as the only desktop environment (traditional menu / panel layout).
   Wayfire and Niri remain off but can be enabled in «Configuration Categories - Desktop
   Environment».
 - ONLYOFFICE preselected instead of LibreOffice (ribbon UI, closer to MS Office UX).
 - Spotify added to the multimedia selection.
 - Disk encryption prompt is skipped (encryption defaults to off).
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="" \
  default-value=#false {
    arch-packages ""
}

- name="profile-developer" \
  dialog-name="User Profile" \
  short-description="Software Developer - Multiple compositors, dev-friendly defaults" \
  long-description="""
Optimised for software development work.

Defaults that change vs. Standard:
 - Wayfire AND Niri preselected; XFCE is off.
 - Zed preinstalled as an additional editor.
 - Standardized C.UTF-8 locale for system messages while keeping regional formats
   (consistent tool output, easier to grep).
 - Unrestricted ptrace enabled (allows attaching debuggers across processes of the same
   user without extra capabilities; gdb, lldb,
   strace, perf, rr, Valgrind, IDE debuggers all work).
 - Core dumps stay enabled (useful for crash analysis).
 - host-name and sudo-timeout are pulled forward and asked up front instead of being hidden
   under «Advanced Settings» (both stay in their normal location too, so you can still
   revise without «Back»).
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="" \
  default-value=#false {
    arch-packages ""
}

- name="profile-server" \
  dialog-name="User Profile" \
  short-description="Server - Headless system, no graphical interface" \
  long-description="""
For headless installations: virtual machines used as build hosts, home servers, NAS guests
on hypervisors such as Synology / Proxmox, and similar setups.

No desktop environment, no browser, no office suite, no terminal emulator package. All
other Ditana defaults are unchanged - including LTS-kernel ZFS, automatic snapshots,
firewalld, and the SSH server.

Ditana intentionally does not preinstall any specific server software here (no nginx, no
database, no container runtime); it is not specified what kind of server this will become.
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="" \
  default-value=#false {
    arch-packages ""
}

- name="profile-quick" \
  dialog-name="User Profile" \
  short-description="Quick Installation - Fastest install (for distro hopping)" \
  long-description="""
Trades several Ditana-specific features for the shortest install time. Use this if you only
want to evaluate Ditana, not work in it long-term - the typical «distro-hopping» scenario.

What is sacrificed for speed:
 - BTRFS instead of ZFS (no parallel DKMS module build, and the initial automatic snapshot
   taken at the end of the install is much faster on BTRFS than the rsync-based Timeshift
   snapshot used by ext4 / xfs).
 - Firefox (Arch package) instead of LibreWolf (the LibreWolf Flatpak download is the
   single longest network step in a default install).
 - Ditana Assistant / local AI is disabled (skips the Ollama model download, several
   hundred megabytes).
 - Disk encryption prompt is skipped (encryption defaults to off).

What is kept (because it does not affect install duration much):
 - All three desktop environments - XFCE, Wayfire and Niri - are preselected, so you can
   compare them in the same system. This is intentional: a few extra packages are
   negligible compared to the items above.

Note: this profile optimises install duration, not the resulting system. The defaults
sacrificed here are exactly what distinguishes Ditana from a generic Arch derivative.
If you intend to use Ditana as a daily driver, pick «Standard» instead.
""" \
  spdx-identifiers="" \
  default-value=#false {
    arch-packages ""
}
